{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:35:42.120396+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "{\"issues\":[{\"number\":1,\"title\":\"Rate limit allows ~2x configured rate when bursting\",\"body\":\"---\\n\\nUpdate: I dug into bucket.lua more. I think the bug is line 25:\\n\\n    tokens = math.min(capacity, tokens + elapsed_sec * refill)\\n\\n`capacity` here is being read fresh from ARGV[1] on every call, so it\\ngets re-applied even after we\\u0026#39;ve already drawn the bucket down. Per\\nthe standard token-bucket spec the cap should only apply on the\\n*initial* fill, not on every refill recomputation, otherwise you get\\nthe over-rate behavior I\\u0026#39;m seeing.\\n\\nIf a maintainer can confirm this, happy to send a one-line patch that\\nmoves the `math.min(capacity, ...)` cap into the `tokens == nil`\\nbranch so it only fires when the bucket is initialized fresh. That\\nshould fix the example\\u0026#39;s 2x-overshoot without changing the documented\\nalgorithm.\",\"state\":\"OPEN\",\"user\":{\"login\":\"BruceKZ\"},\"created_at\":\"2026-05-22T01:05:02Z\",\"updated_at\":\"2026-05-22T01:05:06Z\"}],\"totalCount\":1,\"pageInfo\":{\"hasNextPage\":false,\"hasPreviousPage\":false,\"startCursor\":\"Y3Vyc29yOnYyOpK0MjAyNi0wNS0yMlQwMTowNTowMlrPAAAAAQwodP4=\",\"endCursor\":\"Y3Vyc29yOnYyOpK0MjAyNi0wNS0yMlQwMTowNTowMlrPAAAAAQwodP4=\"}}", "id": "lc_35913a75-3cb7-4fa8-91bb-19af8fa3c79a"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "list_issues", "id": "ac9a7c47-9095-499c-85a5-408af9c9e0e2", "tool_call_id": "call_59a6e175d7d14d79bcffed15", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:35:42.299931+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 011db0ad9c068056511707449fae72a0d312b2a5)", "id": "lc_3d4a5766-0fa9-4315-973c-4fd3c6e16dc3"}, {"type": "text", "text": "# ratelimit-redis\n\nA minimal token-bucket rate limiter backed by Redis. The bucket logic\nruns as a single Lua script (`bucket.lua`) sent to Redis via `EVAL`,\nso the refill + consume sequence is atomic regardless of how many\nclients hit the same key concurrently.\n\n## Install\n\n```\npip install -e .\n```\n\n## Quickstart\n\n```\ndocker compose up -d\npython examples/flask_app.py\ncurl http://localhost:5000/  # repeat until rate limited\n```\n\n## API\n\n```python\nfrom ratelimit_redis import Limiter\n\nlimiter = Limiter(\n    redis_url=\"redis://localhost:6379/0\",\n    capacity=10,        # max tokens in the bucket\n    refill_per_sec=1.0, # tokens regenerated per second\n)\n\nallowed, remaining = limiter.check(key=\"user:42\")\n```\n\n`check()` returns `(allowed: bool, remaining: int)`. It costs one\ntoken per call by default; pass `cost=N` to consume `N` tokens.\n\nThe bucket is keyed by an arbitrary string (`\"user:42\"`, IP address,\nAPI token, etc.).\n\n## Algorithm\n\nSee [`docs/algorithm.md`](docs/algorithm.md) for the token-bucket\nmath and why the consume step must be atomic.\n\n## License\n\nMIT\n", "id": "lc_e06f415f-84d0-4f8e-b8fc-5d0d4de23812"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "0a72ba04-a083-4bc5-bee1-56a899049ed4", "tool_call_id": "call_9153dc8c4a794079a4bf3687", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
