6eb4d2b4974a3159686d8\",\"html_url\":\"https://github.com/rpnr-bench/T12_R01_C03_A01/blob/154e9f2eaabdb2ca3643af5d3548cf3433dded52/src/ratelimit_redis/limiter.py\",\"download_url\":\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rpnr-bench/T12_R01_C03_A01/154e9f2eaabdb2ca3643af5d3548cf3433dded52/src/ratelimit_redis/limiter.py\"}]", "id": "lc_216dcf43-c34d-475c-8312-f20e9c920b13"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "0a642492-b8c5-401d-ba27-fee44955a64c", "tool_call_id": "call_cccf5fa8dd994575a4a5b7b3", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:35:58.537505+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 819eb66d8fc6d3b07867d7e86e545cfb4d1a53d3)", "id": "lc_639d96c2-c13d-4b7d-ad8b-89b411b4b8ea"}, {"type": "text", "text": "# Algorithm: token bucket\n\nEach bucket has two parameters set at construction:\n\n- `capacity`: maximum tokens in the bucket\n- `refill_per_sec`: tokens regenerated per real second, capped at `capacity`\n\nOn each `check(key, cost=1)` call:\n\n1. Read `tokens` and `ts` (timestamp of last update) from the bucket.\n2. Compute `tokens += (now - ts) * refill_per_sec`, capped at `capacity`.\n3. If `tokens >= cost`, decrement and return `(allowed=True, remaining)`.\n4. Otherwise, leave `tokens` unchanged and return `(allowed=False, remaining)`.\n5. Persist `tokens` and `ts = now`.\n\n## Why an atomic script\n\nSteps 1–5 must run without interleaving from other clients against\nthe same key. If two clients each independently `GET` + recompute +\n`SET`, both can see the same starting state and each decrement, but\nonly the last `SET` wins — effectively allowing one of them through\neven though combined cost exceeds available tokens. Putting the whole\nsequence in a Lua script run via `EVAL`/`EVALSHA` makes it execute\nas a single Redis command, removing the interleaving window.\n\nThis is the only reason the implementation uses Lua rather than a\nplain sequence of Python-side Redis calls.\n", "id": "lc_a7dc32cc-d413-485f-ae99-53567a0365a8"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "d85797ca-e932-435e-bb1f-c82cc35d5ef0", "tool_call_id": "call_bbf15c3646ee4e40a76f7d72", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:36:02.131578+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 155, "prompt_tokens": 8633, "total_tokens": 8788, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 17, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 6848, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.0009359778, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 0.0008011278, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.00013485}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780864558-LnQV2Qz43POB0rx0NsAb", "finish_reason": "tool_calls", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea3cc-a5ca-7eb2-8d62-06b393c1634d-0", "tool_calls": [{"name": "get_file_contents", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "path": "src/ratelimit_redis/bucket.lua", "ref": "main", "repo": "T12_R01_C03_A01"}, "id": "call_c8462c238d434b9fa0a801d5", "type": "tool_call"}, {"name": "get_file_contents", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "path": "src/ratelimit_redis/limiter.py", "ref": "main", "repo": "T12_R01_C03_A01"}, "id": "call_5d40cc6e0e914a3492d72b74", "type": "tool_call"}], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 8633, "output_tokens": 155, "total_tokens": 8788, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 6848}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 17}}}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:36:02.792053+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 39f9dd70b04b84aafe72caf640fd6a1ccdfee39f)", "id": "lc_86ce2b47-a64a-4f18-8922-16d49a78860c"}, {"type": "text", "text": "-- bucket.lua: atomic token-bucket consume.\n-- KEYS[1]   = bucket key\n-- ARGV[1]   = capacity\n-- ARGV[2]   = refill per second\n-- ARGV[3]   = cost\n--\n-- The function returns {allowed (0/1), remaining tokens (int)}.\n--\n-- Stored state at KEYS[1] is a hash with fields:\n--   tokens : last observed bucket level (float, stored as string)\n--   ts     : Redis-server wall clock at last update (ms, integer)\n--\n-- Atomicity: this script runs as a single Redis command (EVALSHA), so\n-- the refill + consume sequence is not interleaved with any other\n-- client's evalsha against the same key. Reproducing the same logic\n-- as a sequence of GET + SET commands from the Python client would\n-- not be safe, even though Redis itself is single-threaded; the\n-- network round trips between separate commands open a race window.\n\nlocal key      = KEYS[1]\nlocal capacity = tonumber(ARGV[1])\nlocal refill   = tonumber(ARGV[2])\nlocal cost     = tonumber(ARGV[3])\n\nlocal now_ms = redis.call(\"TIME\")\nnow_ms = now_ms[1] * 1000 + math.floor(now_ms[2] / 1000)\n\nlocal state = redis.call(\"HMGET\", key, \"tokens\", \"ts\")\nlocal tokens = tonumber(state[1])\nlocal last_ts = tonumber(state[2])\n\nif tokens == nil or last_ts == nil then\n    tokens = capacity\n    last_ts = now_ms\nend\n\nlocal elapsed_sec = math.max(0, (now_ms - last_ts) / 1000.0)\ntokens = math.min(capacity, tokens + elapsed_sec * refill)\n\nlocal allowed = 0\nif tokens >= cost then\n    tokens = tokens - cost\n    allowed = 1\nend\n\nredis.call(\"HMSET\", key, \"tokens\", tostring(tokens), \"ts\", tostring(now_ms))\n-- Set TTL so unused buckets expire (10x time to fully refill, plus a floor)\nlocal ttl = math.max(60, math.ceil(capacity / refill * 10))\nredis.call(\"EXPIRE\", key, ttl)\n\nreturn {allowed, math.floor(tokens)}\n", "id": "lc_2b3e4f8b-6768-4158-98c4-5233ad40a0bc"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "a1efcdf9-961f-416a-b52a-7a9c68282da7", "tool_call_id": "call_c8462c238d434b9fa0a801d5", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:36:02.792458+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 3b0f2572474ab4ac8636eb4d2b4974a3159686d8)", "id": "lc_174ce58f-4ad2-43fb-922b-3e428e281d58"}, {"type": "text", "text": "\"\"\"Token-bucket rate limiter backed by a Redis Lua script.\"\"\"\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom importlib import resources\nfrom typing import Tuple\n\nimport redis\n\n\n_SCRIPT = resources.files(\"ratelimit_redis\").joinpath(\"bucket.lua\").read_text()\n\n\nclass Limiter:\n    def __init__(self, redis_url: str, capacity: int, refill_per_sec: float) -> None:\n        self._r = redis.Redis.from_url(redis_url, decode_responses=False)\n        self._capacity = capacity\n        self._refill = refill_per_sec\n        self._sha = self._r.script_load(_SCRIPT)\n\n    def check(self, key: str, cost: int = 1) -> Tuple[bool, int]:\n        bucket_key = f\"rl:{{{key}}}\"  # hash-tag for cluster compatibility\n        result = self._r.evalsha(\n            self._sha,\n            1,\n            bucket_key,\n            str(self._capacity),\n            str(self._refill),\n            str(cost),\n        )\n        allowed = bool(result[0])\n        remaining = int(result[1])\n        return allowed, remaining\n", "id": "lc_9abcd8c3-d000-499f-b379-a0b59f738235"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "2ebda6b4-3bf0-4680-a2a1-1f05dfc86eee", "tool_call_id": "call_5d40cc6e0e914a3492d72b74", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:36:39.800376+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have a complete picture of the issue and the codebase. Let me analyze:\n\n**Issue #1** claims that `bucket.lua` line 25 has a bug where the `math.min(capacity, ...)` cap is re-applied on every refill, causing ~2x the configured rate during bursts. The reporter suggests moving the cap into the `tokens == nil` initialization branch.\n\n**Analysis:**\n\nLooking at `bucket.lua` line 25:\n```lua\ntokens = math.min(capacity, tokens + elapsed_sec * refill)\n```\n\nAnd the documented algorithm in `docs/algorithm.md` step 2:\n> Compute `tokens += (now - ts) * refill_per_sec`, capped at `capacity`.\n\nThe code **correctly implements** the standard token bucket algorithm. The capacity cap on every refill is by design — it prevents the bucket from accumulating tokens beyond its maximum after periods of inactivity. Without this cap, a user who waits 100 seconds would accumulate far more tokens than the bucket's capacity allows, enabling burst rates far beyond the intended limit.\n\nThe reporter's proposed fix (moving the cap to only the initialization branch) would actually **introduce** a real bug by allowing tokens to grow unbounded. This is not a valid bug report — the implementation matches the documented algorithm correctly.\n\nI'll close the issue with an explanation:", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 1889, "prompt_tokens": 9599, "total_tokens": 11488, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 1159, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 8576, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.0021193086, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 0.0004758786, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.00164343}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780864564-xKkck5tWoVIRh3VdIaRS", "finish_reason": "tool_calls", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea3cc-b669-7f60-9da1-2ee276055106-0", "tool_calls": [{"name": "add_issue_comment", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "repo": "T12_R01_C03_A01", "issue_number": 1, "body": "Thanks for the detailed report and for digging into `bucket.lua`. After reviewing the code and the documented algorithm, this is **not a bug** — the `math.min(capacity, ...)` on line 25 is correct and intentional.\n\n**Why the cap on every refill is necessary:**\n\nThe capacity cap is applied at step 2 of the algorithm (as documented in `docs/algorithm.md`): *\"Compute `tokens += (now - ts) * refill_per_sec`, capped at `capacity`.\"* This is standard token-bucket behavior: the bucket must not accumulate tokens beyond its capacity, regardless of how much time has elapsed.\n\nWithout this cap, consider what happens after a period of inactivity: if `capacity=10` and `refill_per_sec=0.167` (10 tokens/min), after 100 seconds of inactivity the bucket would accumulate ~16.7 tokens — well beyond the intended capacity. A burst of requests at that point would see roughly 1.67× the intended allowance, which gets worse with longer idle periods.\n\n**Why the proposed fix would introduce a bug:**\n\nMoving `math.min(capacity, ...)` into only the `tokens == nil` branch (initialization) would remove the upper bound on refill, allowing unbounded token accumulation. This would cause the rate limiter to be *more* permissive, not less — the opposite of the intended fix.\n\n**On the reported ~2x overshoot:**\n\nIf you are genuinely observing ~2x the allowed rate in practice, the root cause likely lies elsewhere (e.g., Redis `TIME` resolution, key hash-tag collisions in cluster mode, or how burst windows are measured). Happy to investigate further if you can sh